We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms and physical examination findings suggest that the patient has pelvic organ prolapse, which is caused by weak supporting structures. Among the options, rectovaginal fascia is responsible for the support of the rectum and vagina and weakness in this area is likely causing the protrusion of the posterior vaginal wall seen on examination.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The bulging of the posterior vaginal wall during Valsalva maneuver suggests a rectocele. Among the options, rectovaginal fascia weakness is the most likely cause of rectocele. Pubocervical fascia weakness can cause cystocele, while uterosacral ligament weakness can cause uterine prolapse. Bulbospongiosus muscle weakness can cause urinary incontinence but not fecal urgency or incomplete evacuation.
